Neural–Spatial Bridge (NSB)

1. Overview

The Neural–Spatial Bridge (NSB) is the translation layer responsible for converting semantic intent and generative neural representations into persistent spatial-runtime structures within IWDS.

It exists because the core IWDS layers operate on fundamentally different substrates:

Domain	Representation
Human Intent	Natural language, symbolic meaning
Generative AI	Latent pattern fields
Simulation Runtime	Explicit spatial objects
Rendering	Perceptual projections (pixels/audio)

Without a bridging mechanism, generative outputs cannot become operational world entities inside a persistent simulation.

The NSB solves this by preserving object identity and operational meaning across substrate transitions.

⸻

2. Architectural Position

The NSB sits between the generative engine and simulation runtime.

User Intent
    ↓
Conversational Director Agent (L3)
    ↓
Generative World Engine (L1)
    ↓
NEURAL–SPATIAL BRIDGE (NSB)
    ↓
Real-Time Simulation Runtime (L2)
    ↓
Perceptual Rendering

The bridge converts generative outputs into runtime-valid spatial entities that can be:
	•	navigated
	•	interacted with
	•	referenced
	•	modified
	•	replayed

⸻

3. Translation Principle

The NSB operates under the Translation Invariant:

A world object remains the same object when its load-bearing meaning survives conversion across representational substrates.

Example:

A “castle” exists across multiple forms:

Substrate	Representation
Language	“Stone castle on a hill”
Latent	diffusion manifold representation
Spatial	mesh + collider + navmesh
Perceptual	rendered fortress

The object is considered successfully bridged when its operational meaning remains intact, not merely its visual similarity.

⸻

4. NSB Translation Pipeline

When a user issues a command, the bridge performs a multi-stage compilation process.

Stage 1 — Intent Extraction

The Director Agent converts natural language into a Semantic Object Specification (SOS).

Example command:

“Place a ruined stone castle on that hill with an interior courtyard.”

Extracted structure:

object_class: castle
material: stone
condition: ruined
location: hill_top
affordances: enterable, traversable
features: courtyard


⸻

Stage 2 — Invariant Binding

The system identifies constraints that must survive translation.

Examples:
	•	structure must be traversable
	•	location must remain hill-top
	•	courtyard must exist
	•	object must persist as a landmark

These invariants are passed to validation systems.

⸻

Stage 3 — Neural Generation

The Generative World Engine produces candidate structures.

Possible representations include:
	•	implicit geometry fields
	•	neural radiance fields
	•	gaussian splat scenes
	•	latent asset templates

Outputs are packaged as Neural Representation Packets (NRP).

⸻

Stage 4 — Spatial Compilation

The NSB converts neural candidates into runtime-valid objects.

Generated components may include:
	•	mesh geometry
	•	collision volumes
	•	navigation meshes
	•	physics tags
	•	interaction anchors
	•	material maps

These components become Spatial Runtime Objects (SRO).

Example structure:

SRO {
  uuid
  mesh_ref
  collider_ref
  navmesh_ref
  transform
  semantic_tags
}


⸻

Stage 5 — Consistency Verification

Pantheon subsystems validate the compiled object.

Pantheon Module	Role
Spider	world graph integrity
Mirror	invariant validation
Hound	anomaly detection

Checks include:
	•	collision conflicts
	•	topology violations
	•	navigation errors
	•	identity collisions

If validation fails, the object is modified or rejected.

⸻

Stage 6 — Runtime Commit

Approved objects are inserted into the simulation.

Operations include:
	•	scene graph insertion
	•	UUID assignment
	•	event ledger logging
	•	navigation recalculation

The object is now part of the persistent world.

⸻

5. Reverse Translation: Spatial → Neural

The NSB also operates in reverse during rendering.

The simulation runtime may store coarse spatial data, while neural systems provide perceptual richness.

Pipeline:

Spatial Runtime State
      ↓
Neural Enhancement Layer
      ↓
Perceptual Rendering

Enhancement may include:
	•	texture detail
	•	lighting refinement
	•	atmospheric effects
	•	cinematic motion

This hybrid model balances runtime stability with perceptual fidelity.

⸻

6. Operating Modes

The NSB supports three modes depending on simulation needs.

Mode I — Asset Synthesis

Neural generation produces explicit spatial assets.

Use cases:
	•	buildings
	•	terrain
	•	characters
	•	vehicles

Advantages:
	•	persistent and interactable

Limitations:
	•	higher compute cost

⸻

Mode II — Neural Overlay

The runtime holds simplified geometry while neural rendering enhances visuals.

Use cases:
	•	lighting
	•	atmospheric effects
	•	stylistic transformations

Advantages:
	•	low computational overhead

Limitations:
	•	visual layer must remain constrained by runtime truth

⸻

Mode III — Hybrid Mode (Default)

Persistent structures exist as spatial assets while high-frequency visual detail remains neural.

Example:

Component	Representation
castle structure	runtime mesh
weather effects	neural overlay
surface texture detail	neural refinement

This provides both stability and visual richness.

⸻

7. Bridge Action Interface

The Director Agent interacts with the NSB through defined action types.

Example actions include:

Instantiate

Create new runtime object.

instantiate(object_class="tower", location="district_west")

Modify

Update attributes.

modify(uuid="obj_147", material="blue_glass")

Relocate

Change position.

relocate(uuid="obj_147", anchor="hill_top")

Restyle

Apply perceptual change.

restyle(uuid="obj_147", style="gothic")

Reconcile

Resolve semantic conflicts.

reconcile(parameter="sky_state", policy="timeline_branch")

These actions form the operational command vocabulary for world modification.

⸻

8. Conflict Resolution

The NSB includes mechanisms for handling contradictory commands.

Examples:

Conflict	Resolution
day vs night	timeline branch
object duplication	identity merge
physics violation	Mirror rejection

Possible policies include:
	•	last-write wins
	•	invariant priority
	•	timeline branching
	•	layered coexistence

